
<handout xml:id="handout-section-2-1-matrix-algebra">
  <title>2.1 Matrix Operations</title>

  <page xml:id="p-2-1-overview">
    <title>Topics and Objectives</title>

    <objectives>
        <title>Topics</title>
    <ul>
      <li>Identity and zero matrices</li>
      <li>Matrix algebra (sums and products, scalar multiplies, matrix powers)</li>
      <li>Transpose of a matrix</li>
    </ul>
    </objectives>

    <objectives workspace="true">
        <title>Goals</title>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <em>Apply</em> matrix algebra, the matrix transpose, and the zero and identity matrices,
        to <em>solve</em> and <em>analyze</em> matrix equations.
      </li>
    </ul>
    </objectives>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <definition xml:id="def-zero-matrix" workspace="true">
      <title>Zero Matrix</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>zero matrix</term> is any matrix whose every entry is zero.
        </p>
        <me>
          0_{2\times 3}=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            0 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 0
          \end{bmatrix},
          \qquad
          0_{2\times 1}=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            0\\
            0
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </definition>


    <definition xml:id="def-identity-matrix" workspace="true">
      <title>Identity Matrix</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <m>n\times n</m> <term>identity matrix</term> has ones on the main diagonal and zeros elsewhere.
        </p>
        <me>
          I_2=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 1
          \end{bmatrix},
          \qquad
          I_3=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 1
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <p>
      Note: Any matrix with dimensions <m>n\times n</m> is <term>square</term>.
      Zero matrices need not be square; identity matrices must be square.
    </p>

    <p><nbsp/></p>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-2-1-sums-scalars">
    <title>Sums and Scalar Multiples</title>

    <p>
      Suppose <m>A\in\mathbb{R}^{m\times n}</m>, and <m>a_{i,j}</m> is the element of <m>A</m>
      in row <m>i</m> and column <m>j</m>.
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          If <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are <m>m\times n</m> matrices, then the elements of <m>A+B</m>
          are <m>a_{i,j}+b_{i,j}</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          If <m>c\in\mathbb{R}</m>, then the elements of <m>cA</m> are <m>c\,a_{i,j}</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <example xml:id="ex-sum-scalar-find-c-k" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If
        </p>
        <me>
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 2 \amp 3\\
            4 \amp 5 \amp 6
          \end{bmatrix}
          + c
          \begin{bmatrix}
            7 \amp 4 \amp 7\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp k
          \end{bmatrix}
          =
          \begin{bmatrix}
            15 \amp 10 \amp 17\\
            4 \amp 5 \amp 16
          \end{bmatrix},
        </me>
        <p>
          what are the values of <m>c</m> and <m>k</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
            Note that we can use rules (a) and (b) above to combine the left expression and get the following equation: <me>\begin{bmatrix} 1 + 7c \amp 2 + 4c \amp 3 + 7c \\ 4 \amp 5 \amp 6 + kc \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 15 \amp 10 \amp 17 \\ 4 \amp 5 \amp 16 \end{bmatrix}</me> Setting corresponding entries equal to one another, we see that <m>c = 2</m> and <m>k = 5</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-2-1-properties-addition-scalars">
    <title>Properties of Sums and Scalar Multiples</title>

    <p>
      Scalar multiples and matrix addition have the expected properties.
      If <m>r,s\in\mathbb{R}</m> are scalars and <m>A,B,C</m> are <m>m\times n</m> matrices, then:
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li><m>A + 0_{m\times n} = A</m></li>
      <li><m>(A+B)+C = A+(B+C)</m></li>
      <li><m>r(A+B)=rA+rB</m></li>
      <li><m>(r+s)A = rA + sA</m></li>
      <li><m>r(sA) = (rs)A</m></li>
    </ol>

    <p><nbsp/></p>


    <definition xml:id="def-matrix-multiplication-columns" workspace="true">
      <title>Matrix Product via Columns</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be an <m>m\times n</m> matrix and <m>B</m> be an <m>n\times p</m> matrix.
          The product <m>AB</m> is an <m>m\times p</m> matrix, given by
        </p>
        <me>
          AB
          =
          A
          \begin{bmatrix}
            \vec b_1 \amp \cdots \amp \vec b_p
          \end{bmatrix}
          =
          \begin{bmatrix}
            A\vec b_1 \amp \cdots \amp A\vec b_p
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      Note: The dimensions of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> determine whether <m>AB</m> is defined,
      and what its dimensions will be.
    </p>

    <image xml:id="img-matrix-multiplication-dimensions" source="./matrix_multi2.png" width="40%">
      <shortdescription>Diagram showing how matrix dimensions match in a product.</shortdescription>
      <description>
        A visual guide to when <m>AB</m> is defined based on inner dimensions.
      </description>
    </image>

    <p><nbsp/></p>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-2-1-row-column-rule">
    <title>Row-Column Rule</title>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-row-column-rule">
      <title>Row-Column Rule for Matrix Multiplication</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>A\in\mathbb{R}^{m\times n}</m> has rows <m>\vec a_i</m> and
          <m>B\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times p}</m> has columns <m>\vec b_j</m>, then each element of
          <m>C=AB</m> is
        </p>
        <me>
          c_{ij}=\vec a_i\cdot \vec b_j.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <example xml:id="ex-row-column-compute" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>Compute the following using the row-column method.</p>
        <me>
          C=AB=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            2 \amp 0\\
            1 \amp -1
          \end{bmatrix}
          \begin{bmatrix}
            3 \amp 0 \amp 1\\
            4 \amp 5 \amp 6
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
            Note that 
        </p>
            <m> \begin{eqnarray*} AB \amp = \amp \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 4 \amp 5 \amp 6 \end{bmatrix}\\ \amp = \amp \begin{bmatrix} 2 \cdot 3 + 0 \cdot 4 \amp 2 \cdot 0 + 0 \cdot 5 \amp 2 \cdot 1 + 0 \cdot 6 \\ 1 \cdot 3 + (-1) \cdot 4 \amp 1 \cdot 0 + (-1) \cdot 5 \amp 1 \cdot 1 + (-1) \cdot 6 \end{bmatrix}\\ \amp = \amp \begin{bmatrix} 6 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\ -1 \amp -5 \amp -5 \end{bmatrix}\end{eqnarray*}</m> 
            <p>Note that this method is faster than using the original definition of matrix multiplication given in <xref ref="def-matrix-multiplication-columns"/>. For example, to compute the first column of <m>AB </m> using the original definition, we would compute the following: <me>\begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} = 3\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1\end{bmatrix} + 4 \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 6 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}</me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-2-1-properties-multiplication">
    <title>Properties and Warnings</title>
    <theorem workspace="true" xml:id="thm-properties-multiplication">
        <title> Properties and Warnings</title>
            <p>
            Let <m>A,B,C</m> be matrices of sizes needed for the products to be defined,
            and suppose <m>A</m> is <m>m\times n</m>.
            </p>

            <ol>
            <li><p><em>Associative:</em> <m>(AB)C = A(BC)</m></p></li>
            <li><p><em>Left distributive:</em> <m>A(B+C)=AB+AC</m></p></li>
            <li><p><em>Right distributive:</em> <m>(A+B)C = AC + BC</m></p></li>
            <li><p><em>Identity:</em> <m>I_m A = A I_n</m></p></li>
            </ol>

            <p><em>Warnings:</em></p>
            <ol>
            <li>
                <p><em>Non-commutative:</em> In general, <m>AB\neq BA</m>.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p><em>Non-cancellation:</em> <m>AB=AC</m> does not imply <m>B=C</m>.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p><em>Zero divisors:</em> <m>AB=0</m> does not imply <m>A=0</m> or <m>B=0</m>.</p>
            </li>
            </ol>
        </theorem>

        <p><nbsp/></p>

    <p>
      The associative property is <m>(AB)C = A(BC)</m>. If <m>C=\vec x</m>, then:
    </p>

    <me>(AB)\vec x = A(B\vec x).</me>

    <p>Schematically:</p>

    <image xml:id="img-associative-flow" width="70%">
      <latex-image>
        <latex>
